If my experience provides any indication, federal and provincial government framework going forward needs to ensure equitable access to the COVID-19 vaccine for all, including non-permanent residents of Ontario. https://t.co/OnudXJTB4v  #COVID19 #vaccination

Getting the flu shot too proved to be a tumultuous experience. I was turned away by pharmacies citing billing inabilities, and @TOPublicHealth‚Äôs flu vaccination clinics were out of appointment slots for weeks.  https://t.co/OnudXJTB4v #COVID19 #OHIP #Ontario

After having tested negative, a test result that took about five times longer than the average time it takes for a health-card holder, my first instinct was to bolster my immune system by getting a flu shot. https://t.co/OnudXJTB4v

Booking and getting a COVID swab test was pretty straightforward, but the process of obtaining the result itself was marred with delays and backed-up voice mailboxes. https://t.co/OnudXJTB4v #COVID19 #Ontario

I write about how experiencing flu symptoms during the fall was especially stressful, as an international student without OHIP coverage.  News that @ONThealth had made all COVID-19 related services free for everyone, came as a massive relief. https://t.co/OnudXJTB4v #COVID19

@mereomstead @sasapetricic @IoannaCBC @davidcommon @Skype @zoom_us @CBC One final piece of advice that @IoannaCBC left the students with, was to do one‚Äôs best and stick with the profession, even during the tough times.  ‚ÄúYou have to be in it for the right reasons.‚Äù üí™ #CJRL723

@mereomstead @sasapetricic @IoannaCBC @davidcommon @Skype @zoom_us @CBC Foreign correspondent @sasapetricic, has reported in many extreme scenarios. He found that the biggest difference between covering warzones and coronavirus is that with the virus "one won't know whether you've had a problem with it until, perhaps days, perhaps even weeks later.‚Äù

@mereomstead @sasapetricic @IoannaCBC @davidcommon @Skype @zoom_us @Davidcommon mentioned that @CBC realizes that not only do they need to have more diversity in their sources, but also hire more BIPOC people to work in their newsrooms. ‚ÄúI am cautiously hopeful that we will do better as an organization internally.‚Äù  #CJRL723

@mereomstead @sasapetricic @IoannaCBC @davidcommon @Skype @zoom_us A student asked about the importance of including marginalized voices in stories, especially those without good internet connectivity. @Sasapetricic admitted that the media can fall in a rut and fail to include diverse representative voices in stories.   #CJRL723 #DiversityInNews

@mereomstead @sasapetricic @IoannaCBC @davidcommon A major challenge reporters are facing is not being able to interview in person. ‚ÄúSuddenly @Skype, FaceTime and @Zoom_us (became) real options,‚Äù said @IoannaCBC. Using these, however, risks losing out on inputs from those without good access to the internet.   #CJRL723

@Dskok observed, ‚ÄúNewsrooms are inherently hierarchical.‚Äù He wrestles with deciding ‚Äúhow much of it is a natural predisposition to not wanting to hear different things, and how much of it is ultimately having to just make decisions in order to keep the production line moving.‚Äù

@Benyt stated, ‚Äú@Google and @Facebook really are starting to enter into financial arrangements with news organizations because they're afraid of regulation, and they're afraid of regulation because media companies, led by @newscorp, are lobbying regulators.‚Äù #CJRL723

@Benyt noted that US news media existing independent of government influence has always been a myth, be it @USPS rigged to favour newspaper publishers in the early 1700s or newspapers getting major revenue from posting governments‚Äô legal notices, "it has also always been there."

@Benyt said @BuzzFeed was conceived as ‚Äúa media company for people to open their computers and go to social sites like @Facebook,  @Twitter and @StumbleUpon and the goal of the media was to get into those streams rather than to bring you to their own destination.‚Äù  #CJRL723

‚ÄúThe opinion section as a platform has evolved. One used to have to get through 20 pages of the A-section to get to the opinion section, so the context was wrapped around it. Now in an internet age, everything's disaggregated so you have no context around each column.‚Äù - @dskok

Solid advice from @WalmsleyGlobe  to budding journalists trying to enter the industry during this time : üîµDemonstrate commitment. üîµBe willing to travel and move to a smaller market. üîµLet bigger banners like @globeandmail be a future goal where you eventually reach. #CJRL723

It's brilliant how üì∞ orgs can inform editorial decisions by tracking audience needs. Phillip Crawley said, ‚ÄúWe've got some of the best data scientists in Canada. The quality of the data that we now get to help inform our decisions every day is really making a huge difference.‚Äù

Digital advertising might seem like the saviour of the news world, but very little of that ad revenue trickles down and actually reaches publishers. As Phillip Crawley mentions, ‚Äùthe learning of the last 20 years is that digital advertising is not going to save your bacon."

Reporting from a distance will be the new normal for the foreseeable future, but journalists seem to be unsure if they prefer it that way. In a survey, about 51% of @globeandmail's staff say they‚Äôd rather keep on working from home at the moment. #WorkFromHome #Journalism #CJRL723
